<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="pair-programming">
  <metadata>
    <tier>free</tier>
    <group>dev</group>
    <domain>software-developer</domain>
    <summary>Driver codes while Navigator reviews and guides. Four modes: classic, Ping-Pong, Strong-Style, Tour Guide. With AI, human drives; agent navigates one instruction per turn.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>pairing</tag>
      <tag>collaboration</tag>
      <tag>knowledge-transfer</tag>
      <tag>tdd</tag>
      <tag>ai-navigator</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2024-04-25</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Pair Programming</title>
    <summary>A practice where two programmers share one workstation: the Driver writes code while the Navigator reviews each line, thinks strategically, and catches errors. Pairs switch roles frequently. Four modes: classic Driver-Navigator, Ping-Pong (TDD), Strong-Style (idea must go through the other person's hands), and Tour Guide (expert narrates codebase to newcomer). With an AI agent, the human is always physically the driver; the agent acts as strategic navigator emitting one bounded instruction per turn.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Pairing produces fewer bugs, accelerates knowledge transfer, and eliminates single points of failure. Short feedback loops (navigator spots error in real-time) are cheaper than review cycles. With an agent as navigator, solo developers get strategic guidance, architectural second opinions, and live code review without a second human.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Complex or unfamiliar code areas where a second perspective prevents wrong-path investment.</item>
        <item>Knowledge transfer: onboarding, cross-training, tour guide through legacy code.</item>
        <item>Critical business logic where correctness matters more than speed.</item>
        <item>TDD ping-pong to stay engaged and alternate test/impl roles.</item>
        <item>AI-assisted pairing: human drives, Claude navigates in strong-style mode.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Simple, routine tasks where overhead exceeds benefit.</item>
        <item>Privacy-sensitive code that cannot leave the local machine — skip cloud agent.</item>
        <item>High-velocity sprints where per-line explanation slows the team below solo velocity.</item>
        <item>Domains where the model is weak (DSP, embedded firmware, niche DSLs) — agent adds noise.</item>
        <item>True multi-developer pairing — adding an agent to a human-human pair fragments attention.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="roles">
      <section name="driver">
        <list>
          <item>Writes the code — focuses on tactical, line-by-line implementation</item>
          <item>Verbalizes thought process ("I'm creating a validator class here because...")</item>
          <item>Asks navigator for input when stuck</item>
          <item>Switches roles when tired or blocked</item>
        </list>
      </section>
      <section name="navigator">
        <list>
          <item>Reviews code in real-time — spots bugs, typos, edge cases</item>
          <item>Thinks strategically about architecture and design</item>
          <item>Keeps track of next steps and open questions</item>
          <item>Guides, does not dictate — suggests, does not demand</item>
        </list>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="four-modes">
      <section name="classic-driver-navigator">
        <p>Driver codes, navigator reviews. Switch every 15-30 minutes. Best for most situations and complex features.</p>
      </section>
      <section name="ping-pong-tdd">
        <p>Person A writes a failing test. Person B makes it pass. Person B writes the next failing test. Person A makes it pass. Best for TDD practice and keeping both engaged.</p>
      </section>
      <section name="strong-style">
        <rule>
          <statement>In Strong-Style, an idea must go through the other person's hands to reach the computer. The navigator dictates; the driver types. The driver must understand before typing.</statement>
          <rationale>Forces the navigator to articulate clearly; driver learns by doing. Best for mentoring and knowledge transfer.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </section>
      <section name="tour-guide">
        <p>Expert guides newcomer through the codebase; newcomer drives. Expert explains architecture, history, and gotchas. Best for onboarding new team members.</p>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-navigator-adaptation">
      <rule>
        <statement>When pairing with an AI agent as navigator, the human is always physically the driver. The agent must emit ONE bounded instruction per turn, explain why, and wait for the human result before the next instruction.</statement>
        <rationale>Multi-step agent instructions degrade into agent-driven solo coding, removing the human from the loop. One instruction at a time maintains the pairing dynamic.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Restate Strong-Style rules every ~10 turns when using an AI navigator. Under length pressure, agents revert to emitting full files.</statement>
        <rationale>Agent context degrades over long sessions; explicit re-statement of the mode contract prevents role drift.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="session-structure">
      <rule>
        <statement>Define the session mode at the start (classic, ping-pong, strong-style, or tour-guide). Do not switch modes mid-session without resetting context.</statement>
        <rationale>Mode ambiguity creates role confusion; explicitly naming the mode aligns both participants on expectations.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Use Pomodoro: 25-minute focused blocks, 5-minute breaks. Switch roles at breaks or natural stopping points. Max 4-6 hours of pairing per day.</statement>
        <rationale>Continuous pairing without breaks causes mental exhaustion, especially remote. The agent does not tire but the human does.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Keep prompts short when working with an AI navigator. Paste diffs and test output, not full files.</statement>
        <rationale>Full files consume context budget and force the agent to re-read code it already knows. Diffs and test output provide targeted feedback.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="skill-level-pairings">
      <section name="expert-novice">
        <p>Use Tour Guide or Strong-Style. Expert navigates more often. Novice drives to learn by doing. Expert must explain why, not just what.</p>
      </section>
      <section name="expert-expert">
        <p>High productivity. Watch for keyboard hogging. Take breaks to avoid fatigue. Good for complex problems.</p>
      </section>
      <section name="novice-novice">
        <p>Longer sessions needed. Focus on learning, not speed. Get expert review after the session.</p>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="remote-tools">
      <list>
        <item>VS Code Live Share — full IDE sharing, free, cross-platform</item>
        <item>Tuple — low-latency, macOS only, paid</item>
        <item>Pop — multi-cursor, free tier</item>
        <item>tmate — terminal pairing fallback</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="session-memory">
      <rule>
        <statement>Run a silent retro at the end of each session: agent generates a 5-bullet summary, human edits it. Persist to a session.md file for next session context.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents reset context between sessions. session.md bridges the gap and ensures continuity across multiple pairing sessions.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="structural-antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Keyboard hog — one person always drives, never switches</description>
        <reason>The non-driver disengages and loses context. Use timer-based switching (25 min).</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Backseat driver — navigator dictates every keystroke instead of guiding strategy</description>
        <reason>Micromanagement frustrates the driver and defeats the purpose of role separation. Trust the driver at the tactical level.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Disengaged observer — navigator zones out, checks phone, multitasks</description>
        <reason>Disengaged navigator provides no value. Use active techniques (Ping-Pong) to keep both participants engaged.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Forced pairing on everything including trivial tasks</description>
        <reason>Pairing overhead exceeds benefit for boilerplate. Choose tasks wisely — pair on complex or knowledge-transfer situations.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Silent pairing — no communication between driver and navigator</description>
        <reason>Silent pairing is just two people sitting together, not pairing. Use the think-aloud protocol.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-specific-antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent emitting full files instead of bounded instructions under length pressure</description>
        <reason>Full-file output removes the human from the loop and turns the session into a review exercise. Restate Strong-Style rules every ~10 turns.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Navigator pollution — agent fills silence with unsolicited rewrites during exploration</description>
        <reason>Unsolicited suggestions interrupt the human's thinking. Explicitly mute the agent: "only answer when I ask".</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent auto-committing work during a pair session</description>
        <reason>Every commit during pairing must be reviewed by the human. Agents should propose; humans decide and commit.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Using an IDE tab-completer (Copilot, Cursor) as a substitute for strategic pairing with a reasoning model</description>
        <reason>Tab completers operate at line level. A reasoning model (Claude) is better as a strategic navigator on architecture. Use the right tool for each layer.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="where-it-fails-limitations">
      <list>
        <item>README defines roles for two humans; with an agent, the human is always physically the driver, but cognitively can be either role. The "who types?" rule has to be redefined per session.</item>
        <item>"Switch every 15-30 min" doesn't apply to an LLM — fatigue model is wrong; instead switch when context depth changes (new file, new layer).</item>
        <item>"Camera on" / "rapport" advice is irrelevant; needs replacement with "share screenshot of failing test" / "share git diff".</item>
        <item>Strong-style ("idea must go through someone else's hands") becomes degenerate with an agent — the agent has no hands. Reinterpret as "agent must articulate a single concrete instruction; human types it verbatim or rejects".</item>
        <item>The methodology treats AI as "sometimes useful" — does not address agent-led pairing as the default mode.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Run pair-programming with an agent as a continuous explain-then-act loop. The human keeps the keyboard; the agent emits one bounded instruction per turn ("add a return type annotation", "extract the validation block to a helper"). After each turn the human accepts, edits, or rejects, and reports the result (test output, diff). Keep transcripts short — paste only the diff and test output back, not the whole file. Solo developer wants a "navigator" presence: Claude as live reviewer while a human drives in VS Code / JetBrains. Strong-style sessions where the human types, the agent dictates the line and explains why. Onboarding scenarios: agent plays "tour guide" through an unfamiliar repo, narrating architecture as the human navigates. TDD ping-pong with a human writing tests and the agent making them pass (and vice versa). Debugging: human shares failing repro, agent navigates hypotheses while human runs commands.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Define the mode at session start: classic, ping-pong, strong-style, or tour-guide. Don't switch mid-session without resetting context.</item>
        <item>One instruction per turn for strong-style with an agent — multi-step instructions degrade into agent-driven solo coding.</item>
        <item>Keep prompts short; paste diffs and test output, not full files. Saves context and forces the agent to ask for what it needs.</item>
        <item>Take real breaks. Agent does not tire, but humans do — Pomodoro still applies on the human side.</item>
        <item>Run a silent retro at session end: agent generates a 5-bullet summary, human edits it. This becomes session memory.</item>
        <item>Use ping-pong specifically when the human is learning a framework — writing the failing test forces understanding of behavior.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="cli-tools">
      <list>
        <item>VS Code Live Share — Share IDE with another human while agent is in chat</item>
        <item>Tuple — Low-latency pairing tool (macOS)</item>
        <item>Pop — Multi-cursor remote pair tool</item>
        <item>tmux + tmate — Terminal pairing fallback</item>
        <item>git diff --staged / gh pr diff — What to paste back to the agent</item>
        <item>entr / watchexec — Re-run tests on save during ping-pong</item>
        <item>claude CLI — Headless agent driver inside terminal</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="services-apps">
      <list>
        <item>Tuple — SaaS. Human-human; agent participates via chat side-channel.</item>
        <item>VS Code Live Share — SaaS (free). Same as Tuple.</item>
        <item>GitHub Codespaces / Gitpod — SaaS. Shared dev environment; agent can be wired into terminal.</item>
        <item>CodeTogether — SaaS. Cross-IDE pairing.</item>
        <item>Slack / Discord — SaaS. Side-channel for agent transcript &amp; retros.</item>
        <item>Miro / Excalidraw — SaaS. Whiteboarding — agents weak at spatial reasoning.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/pair-session.sh" purpose="Shell script: start a logged pair session with script(1) for terminal transcript."/>
      <template path="templates/strong-style-prompt.txt" purpose="Strong-style AI-navigator system prompt: one instruction per turn, explain why, wait for result."/>
    </templates>

